A Honeywell employee was among four people killed in a plane crash near Dubai airport. JOHANNESBURG - US tech giant Honeywell, says it does not own or operate the aircraft that crashed close to Dubai airport in the United Arab Emirates. The crash claimed the lives of three British people and a South African. Media reports on Thursday claimed that the crash belonged to Honeywell. READ: South African, three Britons killed in Dubai plane crash However, the tech giant says a third party is involved. “We are deeply saddened by yesterday’s plane crash in Dubai, and our heartfelt condolences are with the victims’ families," Honeywell said in a statement. "The plane was not owned or operated by Honeywell but by a third party engaged by Honeywell. We are waiting for more details."